abstract={An experiment was conducted to show the electronic conductivity in mixed-valence tellurium oxides. Cs(M,Te)2O6 oxides were prepared from appropriate quantities of CsNO3, TeO2/H 6TeO6, and an oxide of M by heating in air at 450 to 650°C. They were characterized by X-ray powder diffraction, dc electrical conductivity, and Seebeck coefficients at 25°C. Neutron diffraction data were collected on three compounds at NIST. Neutron diffraction studies were conducted on CsGe1/2Te3/2O6 and CsAl 1/3Te5/3O6 samples in an effort to determine if their relatively high conductivities might be due to detectable deviations from ideal stoichiometry or ideal structure. It was concluded that the number of associated filled 5s states is significant enough to produce color and sometimes electronic conductivity but may be very small, especially relative to CsTe 2O6.},
